Did you know that the moon is exactly the right size to cover up the sun during an eclipse, while still allowing the corona to be visible? And on top of that, it is in the exact right obrit for it to possibly go exactly between the sun and earth.


If it was just 1m bigger or smaller that it would allow us to see the sun, or it would make it totally invisible.And if it were on any other orbit it would never cross exactly between the sun and the earth. Given that the moon is 3,474.2km across that means that it's 3,474,200m. That means the chance of this being a coincidence are a crazy 1 in 3,474,200!


Also the chance of it possibly being in the same orbit which overlaps is also unbelievable. The moon has a width of about 0.5 degrees on the sky, meaning with a = pi x r^2, a = pi x 0.25^2 = 0.2 degrees squared. The area of the entire sky is the area of a sphere and the radius would be 1 radian, so 57.3 degrees, so in degrees squared that's 4 x pi x r^2 = 4 x pi x 57.3^2 = 41,259 degrees squared. Therefore the chance of it covering the same part as the sun is 0.2 in 41,259, or 1 in 206,295.


The chance of both therefore is 1/206295 x 1/3474200 = 1 in 716710089000!!! Bahaha how can atheists think there's no god when things like this exist? That effectively means that the chance of there being no god is 1 in 716710089000. Who would take those odds, especially when eternal damnation in hell will await you if you lose.


I've just proven that God exists. God isn't some theory, God is a mathematical fact. If you don't believe in him then you're an unscientific fool. God must and does exist, it's impossible for this to have happened without his power.

snippet.textDisplay:
Alighting on a dusty rock,
Neil stepping out to fanfare,
the Eagle’s footprints in the chalk:
potential. Dreams of “elsewhere”.

In temporary awestruck truce,
our enemies were allies.
For what man could not be seduced
by our collective sunrise?

But we returned, and stayed below,
invoking “safety”, stalling.
It’s time for liftoff, time to go,
to run. The stars are calling.

What can unite us by the sky,
what harbor from damnation?
An embassy supported by
the pillars of creation.

We’re pioneers of space and stars,
the universe shall see us!
We’ll set off fireworks on Mars,
we’ll grow a rose on Venus.

The seeds were sown, it’s time to reap.
The harvest ready, sprawling.
First one small step, one giant leap-
Now - Run! The stars are calling!

2:21 or 2:22,


Bonus Urine fact:

Yuri Gagarin was of course the first human in space; a Soviet Union cosmonaut. During the bus ride
out to his rocket - Vostok 1, he realised he had to pee. He decided to relieve himself on a back tire of
the bus. For the cosmonauts who came after, it was considered bad luck not to do this on one's journey

Great video...but it was: "That's one small step for man; one giant leap for mankind." I know because I was 15 at the time, watching on our black and white TV, and was stunned to hear Walter Cronkite say sometime afterwards (a week or two later perhaps?) that it was: "That's one small step for a man; one giant leap for mankind.", though he did get it right immediately after Armstrong said it. In those days I was innocent, so I was confused. It was quite clear what he said. These days I'm not so innocent. People (most, or many people that is) believe what they want to believe. I don't know why Cronkite changed his tune on it though. Maybe he just didn't want to crap on Neil Armstrong's big moment. Shit happens, and Armstrong pooped one out there.
